content.text:
`bun run lint:fix` and “save” are almost certainly using different formatters.

The repo is configured so the CLI runs Biome:

```4:14:package.json
  "scripts": {
    "start": "vite build && electrobun dev",
    "dev": "vite build && electrobun dev --watch",
    "dev:hmr": "concurrently \"bun run hmr\" \"bun run start\"",
    "hmr": "vite --port 5173",
    "build:canary": "vite build && electrobun build --env=canary",
    "build:stable": "vite build && electrobun build --env=stable",
    "lint": "biome check .",
    "lint:fix": "biome check --write .",
    "check": "bun run lint && bunx tsc --noEmit",
    "check:fix": "biome check --write . && bunx tsc --noEmit",
```

And Biome has its own formatting rules plus import organization enabled:

```1:27:biome.json
{
  "$schema": "https://biomejs.dev/schemas/1.9.4/schema.json",
  "organizeImports": {
    "enabled": true
  },
  "formatter": {
    "enabled": true,
    "indentStyle": "space",
    "indentWidth": 2,
    "lineWidth": 100
  },
  "linter": {
    "enabled": true,
    "rules": {
      "recommended": true
    }
  },
  "javascript": {
    "formatter": {
      "semicolons": "always"
    }
  },
  "files": {
    "include": ["src/**/*", "shared/**/*"],
    "ignore": ["dist", "node_modules"]
  }
}
```

But the workspace does not pin the editor formatter on save:

```1:3:.vscode/settings.json
{
    "typescript.tsdk": "node_modules/typescript/lib"
}
```

So on save, Cursor/VS Code is probably using your global formatter settings or another extension, while `bun run lint:fix` uses Biome. That difference explains why the file changes again after running the script.

If you want them to match, set the workspace to use Biome on save too. I can add the `.vscode/settings.json` entries for that if you want.
